About Classes, Inheritance, and Râ€™s Object-Oriented Systems

In object-oriented programming, code is oriented around â€œobjectsâ€. â€œClassesâ€ are definitions of types of objects that share the same attributes and functionality. For more information, see the Wikipedia article.

In the concept of inheritance, children classes are extensions of their parent class in that theyâ€”generally speakingâ€”are a superset of their parent class. Children classes â€œinheritâ€ attributes and functionality from their parent classes. This reporter graphs the inheritance between the classes of a package, with inheritance as a directed edge from a child class to its parent class.

R has four main object-oriented systems: S3, S4, and Reference Classes are part of base R; the R6 package provides another commonly used system.

This reporter supports the S4, Reference Class, and R6 systems. S3 classes are not supported because their inheritance is defined on an ad hoc per-object basis, rather than formally by class definitions.

For more info about Râ€™s built-in object-oriented systems, check out the relevant chapter in Hadley Wickhamâ€™s Advanced R. For more info about R6, check out their documentation website or the chapter in Advanced Râ€™s second edition.
